// 02a-related-classical-qspr — Classical QSPR for thermophysical properties

The prediction of physical properties from molecular structure has a long intellectual history, beginning with additive and topological approaches that predate modern computing. In 1947, Harry Wiener introduced the _path number_---now called the Wiener index---defined as the sum of shortest-path distances between all pairs of non-hydrogen atoms in a molecular graph @Wiener1947. Wiener demonstrated that this single topological descriptor could predict the boiling points of paraffin hydrocarbons with surprising accuracy, establishing the foundational principle that graph-theoretic invariants encode physically meaningful structural information. Nearly three decades later, Milan Randic proposed the molecular connectivity index, computed from vertex degrees of the hydrogen-suppressed molecular graph, and showed that it correlates with boiling point, molar volume, and other properties across diverse compound classes @Randic1975. In parallel, Corwin Hansch and Toshio Fujita formalized the linear free-energy relationship (LFER) paradigm through their $rho$-$sigma$-$pi$ analysis @HanschFujita1964, and the subsequent Hansch--Leo compendium of substituent constants @HanschLeo1979 provided the hydrophobic, electronic, and steric parameters that underpinned an entire generation of quantitative structure--activity and structure--property relationship models.

The group contribution (GC) approach extended these ideas to engineering property estimation. Benson and Buss formalized a hierarchy of additivity schemes---atomic, bond, and group additivity---for thermochemical properties in 1958 @Benson1958, with Benson refining these into a comprehensive tabulation in the second edition of _Thermochemical Kinetics_ @Benson1976. Although Benson group additivity was developed primarily for ideal-gas thermochemistry, it established the core principle that molecular properties can be decomposed into transferable, structure-dependent increments. Joback and Reid extended the GC paradigm to a broader set of engineering properties in 1987, proposing a unified table of 41 first-order functional groups to estimate eleven pure-component properties, including liquid dynamic viscosity @Joback1987. Their viscosity correlation takes the Andrade form $ln mu = sum_i N_i a_i - 1\/T + sum_i N_i b_i$, where $N_i$ is the count of group $i$ and $a_i$, $b_i$ are fitted group contributions. The Joback--Reid method became the de facto baseline for GC property estimation because of its simplicity and wide applicability, though its first-order-only decomposition cannot distinguish structural isomers. Constantinou and Gani addressed this limitation in 1994 by introducing a two-level estimation scheme, where second-order groups capture proximity effects and enable isomer differentiation @Constantinou1994. Marrero and Gani further extended this architecture to three levels in 2001, adding third-order groups encoding fused ring systems and multi-functional interactions across nine properties for over 2000 compounds @Marrero2001.

For mixture viscosity, the UNIFAC (UNIQUAC Functional-group Activity Coefficients) framework, originally developed by Fredenslund, Jones, and Prausnitz for vapor--liquid equilibrium @Fredenslund1975, was adapted by Cao, Knudsen, Fredenslund, and Rasmussen to create the UNIFAC-VISCO method @Cao1993. This approach couples the UNIFAC activity-coefficient model with an Eyring-type viscosity equation, decomposing mixture viscosity into combinatorial and residual contributions using the same VLE group-interaction parameters. The method enables, in principle, the prediction of mixture viscosity without any mixture viscosity data. Temperature dependence remains the central challenge for GC-based viscosity estimation. Most GC approaches adopt the Andrade equation, $ln mu = A + B\/T$, where both $A$ and $B$ are computed as sums of group contributions. More sophisticated treatments use three-parameter forms or embed GC parameters into the Vogel--Fulcher--Tammann equation to capture the steep viscosity rise near the glass transition. Despite these refinements, GC methods for viscosity remain substantially less accurate than those for boiling points or critical constants, with typical errors ranging from 10 to 30% and degraded performance for branched, polyfunctional, or high-molecular-weight compounds where the assumption of group transferability breaks down. Modern open-source implementations, notably the Python library `chemicals` developed by Caleb Bell as part of the Chemical Engineering Design Library @Bell2025chemicals, have made Joback--Reid, Constantinou--Gani, and other GC methods programmatically accessible. The standard reference for selecting among GC methods remains _The Properties of Gases and Liquids_ by Poling, Prausnitz, and O'Connell @Poling2001.

Through the 1990s and 2000s, the QSPR paradigm expanded beyond simple topological indices and group contributions to encompass large-scale molecular descriptor enumeration. Alan Katritzky and collaborators at the University of Florida developed the CODESSA (Comprehensive Descriptors for Structural and Statistical Analysis) software platform, which combined constitutional, topological, geometrical, electrostatic, quantum-chemical, and thermodynamic descriptors---over 800 in total---with automated multilinear regression and heuristic variable-selection algorithms @Katritzky1995. Katritzky and Chen applied this framework directly to liquid viscosity, constructing a five-descriptor linear model for 361 diverse organic compounds that achieved $R^2 = 0.854$ @Katritzky2000viscosity. A comprehensive 2010 review by Katritzky and colleagues surveyed the full landscape of structure--property correlations across dozens of physical and chemical properties @Katritzky2010. In parallel, Stanton and Jurs introduced charged partial surface area (CPSA) descriptors that combined 3D molecular surface area information with electrostatic charge distributions, producing descriptors with direct physical interpretability for properties governed by intermolecular interactions such as surface tension and viscosity @StantonJurs1990. For surface tension specifically, Gharagheizi demonstrated that a six-descriptor linear model could predict values across 320 organic compounds with $R^2 = 0.96$ on the training set @Gharagheizi2006, while Knotts, Wilding, Oscarson, and Rowley showed that the DIPPR evaluated-data repository could serve as a high-quality training set for QSPR surface tension models @Knotts2001.

The descriptor computation ecosystem matured considerably through the 2000s and 2010s. Roberto Todeschini and Viviana Consonni developed the Dragon descriptor calculator, which by version 5.4 could compute over 1,600 descriptors organized into 20 logical blocks covering constitutional, topological, geometrical, and electrostatic categories @MauriDragon2006. Their accompanying two-volume reference _Molecular Descriptors for Chemoinformatics_ systematically catalogued over 5,000 descriptor formulations and became the de facto encyclopedia of the field @Todeschini2009. Because Dragon was commercial software, open-source alternatives emerged. Chuen Wei Yap released PaDEL-Descriptor in 2011, a Java-based platform computing 797 1D/2D descriptors, 134 3D descriptors, and 10 types of fingerprints @Yap2011. Most consequentially, Greg Landrum's RDKit---originally developed at Rational Discovery and released as open-source under a BSD license in 2006---provided a Python/C++ toolkit for descriptor calculation, substructure searching, and fingerprint generation (Morgan/ECFP, MACCS, atom pairs, topological torsions) that became the dominant platform in both academic and industrial cheminformatics @Landrum2006RDKit. The Morgan circular fingerprints @Morgan1965, extended by Rogers and Hahn into the ECFP family @Rogers2010, remain the most widely used molecular representations in property prediction, and their computation through RDKit has become standard practice.

Despite the successes of classical QSPR, these methods face well-documented limitations that motivate the present work. The reliance on multilinear regression assumes that property responses are linear combinations of descriptors, an assumption that fails for properties like viscosity, which depends nonlinearly on molecular size, shape, and intermolecular forces. The descriptor explosion problem---thousands of candidate descriptors versus tens or hundreds of training compounds---creates severe risks of overfitting and chance correlations, requiring careful cross-validation that was not always employed in early studies. The applicability domain of any QSPR model is inherently limited to the chemical space represented in the training data, making extrapolation to novel structural classes unreliable. Many topological descriptors are highly intercorrelated, rendering physical interpretation of multivariate models ambiguous. Perhaps most fundamentally, hand-crafted descriptors may fail to capture the structural features most relevant to a specific property. These limitations motivated the transition first to nonlinear machine-learning methods---random forests @Breiman2001, gradient-boosted trees @Chen2016, and support vector machines---and ultimately to representation-learning approaches that discover task-relevant molecular features directly from structure, as discussed in subsequent sections.
